                            jump to other results
                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" htag="li" hclass="sense" id="ancientmariner_sng_1"><span class="sensetop" htag="span" hclass="sensetop"><span class="def" htag="span" hclass="def">a long poem (1798) by <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/samuel-taylor-coleridge" title="Samuel Taylor Coleridge definition"><span class="ndv">Samuel Taylor Coleridge</span></a>. In it an old sailor tells a wedding guest how he once shot an <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/albatross#albatross_topg_1" title="albatross definition"><span class="ndv">albatross</span></a> <span class="gloss" hclass="gloss" htag="span">(= a large sea bird considered lucky by sailors)</span>. His friends hung the bird around his neck as a punishment. They all died of <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/thirst_1#thirst_sng_2" title="thirst definition"><span class="ndv">thirst</span></a>, and he was left alive to tell his story to anyone who would listen. The best-known lines from the poem are these: <span class="blockquote"><span class="p-g"><span class="wrap_open">“</span><span class="p">Water, water, everywhere</span><span class="p">Nor any drop to drink.</span><span class="wrap_close">”</span></span></span></span></span>    <div id="ring-links-box">
